eceased","1289":"1289","1255":"1255","1266":"1266","1210":"1210","1331":"1331","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1229":"1229","Checkenden,Oxford,England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Checkenden,Oxfordshire,England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Checkenden, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Justice","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name from Middle English <i>justice</i>, <i>justis(e)</i> ‘judicial officer; judge’, Old French <i>justise</i>, <i>justice</i> ‘uprightness; equity; vindication of right; court of justice; judge’, Latin <i>iustitia</i>, a derivative of <i>iustus</i> (see   Just  ).","African American: adoption of the surname in 1 above, because of its literal meaning in English ‘uprightness; equity; vindication of right’."],"variants":[{"name":"Justiss","meanings":["English: variant of   Justice  ."]},{"name":"Justis","meanings":["English: variant of   Justice  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jestice","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Justice  ."]},{"name":"Just","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Christoph, Ernst, Gerhart, Heinz, Helmut, Hildegarde, Horst, Otto, Reinhard, Reinhold.","English, Scottish, German, Danish, Catalan, French, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, Croatian, and Hungarian: from a personal name, from Latin <i>Justus</i>, from <i>justus</i> ‘just, upright’. There were several early Christian saints of this name, among them a 4th-century bishop of Lyon and a 6th-century bishop of Urgell in Catalonia. Compare   Yust  .","English: occasionally perhaps from a nickname, whether French or English, meaning ‘the just one’."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Justice was born in 1230, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Robert LeJustice. She married William Marmion. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1289, in Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1230–1289":"1230–1289","1229–1266":"1229–1266","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1260–1331":"1260–1331","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1289":"1289","1255":"1255","1266":"1266","1210":"1210","1331":"1331","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1229":"1229","Checkenden,Oxford,England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Checkenden,Oxfordshire,England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Checkenden, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1230–1289":"1230–1289","1229–1266":"1229–1266","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","1260–1331":"1260–1331","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1289":"1289","1255":"1255","1266":"1266","1210":"1210","1331":"1331","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1229":"1229","Checkenden,Oxford,England":"Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yh